The Grasshopper Years of Latin America
Bad news continues to accumulate these days in Latin America.
Economic conditions are deteriorating almost everywhere, social cohesion is fraying, and political instability is growing.
It's no surprise since the majority of Latin American countries have spent the last twenty years going nowhere.
The funds were sold and national debts were excessively increased, but nothing lasting and beneficial was achieved.
These years have really been eaten up by locusts.
Over the last 20 years, the annual growth rate of per capita GDP in Latin America has averaged 0.35%.
At this rate, an economy would take 200 years to double.
In Asia, the standard of living doubles every decade.
With such an anemic growth, how can Latin America hope to compete in the global marketplace except through a timid increase in wages?
Economic stagnation is the responsibility of bad governance, not bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may begin to look more and more like Africa — a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and widespread poverty.
Four factors placed her on this path.
First, in the rush toward privatization, everything, from public services to manufacturing industries, was auctioned off.
For a brief period, capital sales helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, revenues from privatization have yielded little in terms of improved infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Worse still, the liquidation of state assets was accompanied by a massive external loan.
In some cases, notably in Argentina, the loans taken by domestic buyers have exhausted all available credit ranges.
Other countries have not reached the level of Argentina, but solvency is a problem in almost all Latin American countries.
Secondly, since the reform did not bring prosperity, the region has become disillusioned with it.
The inflow of capital created a wealth effect, but only as long as they existed.
When the money stopped flowing freely, wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would commit to another decade of structural reforms that would test the patience of average Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without a greater number of deep reforms, too few prerequisites for economic growth will be met to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma announces the third factor: incompetent policies.
Governments that operated along technocratic lines and viewed economic growth as a rising tide that lifts all boats have disappeared.
In Argentina, clumsy presidents keep coming one after another.
Institutions are crumbling, property rights are being called into question, and a random and even more corrupt redistribution effort is underway.
Peru and Venezuela have little more chance; Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Lula Ignacia da Silva and his team, who are leading opinion polls in the period preceding the Brazilian presidential elections, indicates that a large part of the Latin American population is prepared to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from the dominant economic and political thinking that capital has already begun to flee— even though elections are only a few months away.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but this stability could well prove to be temporary.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance deteriorates further, the economy risks a hard landing.
As for all the good news regarding Mexico's emerging democracy, its president is beginning to justify the fears that existed about it: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what it has to do.
The last factor concerns the desperately low savings rate that is endemic to the Americas.
Indeed, this is the economic financial result, because where there is little savings, there is little investment - and thus little foundation for accumulating capital and increasing productivity.
Venezuela now longs for the fat 1970s of OPEC -- which it did not participate in, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
The wealth of Argentina is now taking a vacation in Miami, perhaps for good.
Brazil and Mexico are perfect examples of countries that have sold their assets and borrowed rather than saving.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates reach nearly 40%, where the current account is in surplus, and where there is no public debt.
Government institutions are in favor of the market, and the population is well-educated, disciplined, and flexible in its learning.
Rewards for taking risks and showing initiative are immediate and highly motivating.
One cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
His per capita GDP is only half that of Brazil's.
But with a growth rate in China's coastal region of about 15% per year, who can seriously doubt that within the next 15 years, it will surpass Brazil?
In China, despite all the huge problems encountered, things continue to go correctly, first of all due to the massive flow of foreign direct investments and the imminent benefits of joining the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to fall apart: governments are backtracking on reforms, and the economy is losing ground compared to the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when unregulated funds were flowing in, but those times are largely gone.
We must therefore expect much worse economic, social, and political news in the years to come.
Demagogues like Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem — an Argentine presidential candidate once again — may seem like a bad joke, but anyone who cares about the fate of Latin America should not laugh.
